Architecture

SIMA is composed of the following major components:

1. Query Interpreter

Converts a user query into a structured retrieval request.

Example:

"What was that memory architecture idea I had yesterday?"

May produce:

{
  "intent": "recall",
  "entities": [
    "memory architecture"
  ],
  "time_reference": "recent",
  "requested_detail": "high"
}
2. Category Router

Routes the query to relevant memory domains before semantic retrieval.

Example:

AI
  |
  +-- Research
       |
       +-- Memory

This reduces the number of candidate memories requiring deeper evaluation.

3. Short-Form Index

Searches compact retrieval representations.

Example:

MEM_001
Category-indexed compressed memory retrieval

MEM_002
Hierarchical memory routing

MEM_003
Graph-based associative memory

MEM_004
Long-context retrieval optimization
4. Relevance Ranker

Ranks candidate memories using multiple signals.

A conceptual scoring function is:

R(m,q) =
    w_s * SemanticSimilarity
  + w_c * CategoryMatch
  + w_t * TemporalRelevance
  + w_e * EntityOverlap
  + w_i * Importance

The weights are experimental and should be benchmarked.

5. Memory Graph

Memories may be connected by explicit relationships.

MEM_001
  |
  +-- related_to --> MEM_004
  |
  +-- derived_from --> MEM_009
  |
  +-- extends --> MEM_021

This enables multi-hop retrieval.

6. Memory Expansion

Only high-confidence candidates are expanded into full memory objects.

This creates progressive retrieval:

Category
    |
    v
Short Form
    |
    v
Candidate
    |
    v
Detailed Memory
    |
    v
Full Memory
7. Context Assembler

Combines selected memories into the final context passed to the model.

The assembler should prioritize:

Relevance
Recency
Confidence
Importance
Relationship coherence
Token budget
Hierarchical Retrieval

SIMA supports multiple retrieval layers:

Level 4 - Category Index
        |
        v
Level 3 - Entity / Keyword Index
        |
        v
Level 2 - Short Retrieval Form
        |
        v
Level 1 - Detailed Summary
        |
        v
Level 0 - Full Memory

Retrieval proceeds from cheap representations to expensive representations.

The system should only descend deeper when additional information is required.

Adaptive Retrieval

SIMA can dynamically change retrieval depth based on confidence.

High confidence:

Query
  |
  v
Category
  |
  v
Top Memory
  |
  v
Answer

Low confidence:

Query
  |
  v
Category
  |
  v
Broad Candidate Set
  |
  v
Graph Traversal
  |
  v
Expanded Memories
  |
  v
Re-ranking
  |
  v
Answer

The intended relationship is:

Retrieval Depth = f(Retrieval Confidence)
Memory Graph

The memory graph is represented as:

G = (V, E)

where:

V = Memory Nodes
E = Relationships Between Memories

Possible relationship types include:

related_to
derived_from
extends
contradicts
supersedes
supports
references

A query may begin at one memory and traverse related memories.

Example:

Memory Architecture
        |
        v
Graph Theory
        |
        v
Network Connectivity
        |
        v
Retrieval Architecture

This allows the system to retrieve conceptual relationships that may not be represented by a single embedding.

Expected Benefits

SIMA is designed to investigate whether indexed progressive retrieval can provide:

Lower retrieval latency
Lower token consumption
Higher effective memory capacity
Reduced context pollution
Improved long-term recall
Better multi-hop memory retrieval
Improved scalability

These are hypotheses, not established results.

Benchmarking

SIMA should be compared against at least:

Baseline A

Flat vector retrieval.

Baseline B

Vector retrieval + reranking.

SIMA

Category routing + short-form retrieval + progressive expansion.

SIMA+

Category routing + short-form retrieval + graph traversal + adaptive expansion.

Measure:

Recall@K
Precision@K
Context Tokens
Retrieval Latency
Compute Cost
Long-Term Recall Accuracy
Multi-Hop Recall Accuracy

The primary hypothesis is:

SIMA

≈ or > Retrieval Quality

while reducing:

Tokens
Latency
Compute

These results must be established empirically.
